Wait - could the `} {} else {` be parsed differently? In JavaScript, `} {} else {` would be a syntax error because you can't have a standalone block between `}` and `else`. 

Actually... `if (...) {} else {` is valid! The empty block IS the if-body. So the mutated code is:
- `else if (condition) {}` - empty body
- `else { return 'insert'; }`

This means when condition is true → empty body, fall through to end of `if(op)`, return `'retain'`.
When condition is false → `return 'insert'`.

These are functionally equivalent to the original for retain and insert ops...

